1.1.2 Remove genes with low/no expression

We cannot do meaningful analyses of genes with very low counts. Keeping only genes with 10 or more total read counts across samples will speed up the analysis.

# prefilter genes, keeping only genes with 10 or more total read counts across samples
total_genes <- nrow(dds)
# message(str_glue("Total number of genes: {total_genes}"))

keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
# message(str_glue("Keeping {sum(keep)} genes."))

dds <- dds[keep, ]

The original number of genes was 60721, and the number of genes kept after filtering is 21485.

1.1.4 Run the DE workflow

The DESeq function is a convenience function from DESeq2 that estimates size factors (normalization) and fits negative binomial GLMs. This includes the following steps:

  • estimating size factors
  • estimating dispersions
  • gene-wise dispersion estimates
  • mean-dispersion relationship
  • final dispersion estimates
  • fitting model and testing
dds <- DESeq(dds, quiet = TRUE)
# message(paste0("Coefficient names are: ", paste(resultsNames(dds), collapse = " ")))

Coefficients in the model are: Intercept, group_trt_vs_untrt.

After the models are fitted, we can test specific pairs of groups for differential expression. For DESeq2, it is recommended to provide the significance cutoff that you wish to use as it affects the multiple testing correction procedure (see docs). Here, we’ll use the false discovery rate (FDR) cutoff that was provided in the config file (0.1).

contrast <- c("group", params$group_test, params$group_reference)
fdr_cutoff <- params$fdr_cutoff

res <- results(dds, contrast=contrast, alpha=fdr_cutoff)
res <- res[order(res$pvalue), ]

1.1.6 Shrink log fold changes for lowly expressed genes

This step does not affect the identification of DE genes, but it can be useful to perform this to obtain more reliable estimates of the log fold changes for visualizations or for ranking genes (e.g. GSEA).

lfc_shrink <- lfcShrink(dds, contrast=contrast, type="ashr")
## using 'ashr' for LFC shrinkage. If used in published research, please cite:
##     Stephens, M. (2016) False discovery rates: a new deal. Biostatistics, 18:2.
##     https://doi.org/10.1093/biostatistics/kxw041
lfc_shrink <- lfc_shrink[order(lfc_shrink$pvalue), ]

Below are MA-plots – a scatter plot of log2 fold changes (on the y-axis) versus the mean of normalized counts (on the x-axis). Here, we show both the default log fold changes (LFC) and the shrunken log fold changes.

DESeq2::plotMA(res, main="Default LFC")

DESeq2::plotMA(lfc_shrink, main="Shrunken LFC")

1.2.2 Output tables with raw counts

Some folks also find it useful to have tables of the raw counts or the normalized counts. The raw counts can be extracted from the DESeq2 object using either assay() or counts(). This file is trt_vs_untrt_counts.tsv, within the deseq2_tables/ directory.

df <- cbind(as.data.frame(rowData(dds)[, 1:4]),
            assay(dds, "counts")) %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column("ens_gene")
write_tsv(df, file.path(outdir, "counts.tsv"))

1.3 Some common plots for DEG analysis

The plots below are some common visualizations for differential expression analysis. Individual plots can be found in the deseq2_figures/trt_vs_untrt/ directory, for easy access to pdf and png files.

1.3.1 PCA

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a dimensionality reduction technique that transforms data into a new coordinate system, where the axes (principal components, or PCs) are ordered by the amount of variance they capture (shown as percentages in the plots below). PC 1 captures the most variance in the data, followed by PC 2, and so on. PCA is often used to visualize the variance in data and to identify how samples cluster together based on their expression profiles.

If group has a significant effect on the variance in the data, we will see that samples cluster together by group in the PCA plot. If we see samples clustering by some other variable (e.g. batch, treatment, age, sex, genotype, etc.), this suggests that this other variable is confounding the results and should be accounted for in the analysis. If this is the case, you may need to include this variable as a covariate in the model design (e.g. design = ~ batch + group).

Note, again, that no covariates are included in this analysis; if you have a more complex experimental setup with additional covariates and/or confounders, the model used in this report is overly simplistic and won’t accurately model your data – please modify and/or contact the BBC.

Here, we will plot the first four principal components, colored by group.

# Make PCA plots
make_PCA <- function(in_dds, cols, PCx=1, PCy=2, ntop){
  if (ntop > nrow(in_dds)) {
    ntop <- nrow(in_dds)
  }
  mat <- assay(in_dds) 
  col_data <- as.data.frame(colData(in_dds))
  
  # row variances
  vars <- genefilter::rowVars(mat)
  vars_rank <- order(vars, decreasing = TRUE)
  
  # get most variable genes
  mat <- mat[vars_rank[1:ntop], ]
  
  pcaData <- prcomp(t(mat))
  
  prop_var <- data.frame(t(summary(pcaData)$importance))
  names(prop_var) = c("sd", "prop", "cum")
  prop_var$num = 1:nrow(prop_var)
  
  #pcaData <- plotPCA(in_dds, intgroup=colnames(colData(in_dds)), returnData=TRUE, ...)
  percentVar <- round(100 * prop_var$prop)
  
  
  df <- cbind(pcaData$x, col_data)
  
  out_patchwork <- list()
  
  for (i in 1:length(cols)){
    gg_args <- list(x=str_glue("PC{PCx}"), y=str_glue("PC{PCy}"), color=cols[i], label="sample")
    gg_args <- lapply(gg_args, function(x) if (!is.null(x)) sym(x))
    out_patchwork <- c(out_patchwork, list(ggplot(df, aes(!!!gg_args)) +
                                             geom_point(size=1) +
                                             scale_color_manual(values = setNames(c("#440154FF","#2A788EFF", ggsci::pal_npg()(length(levels(dds$group))-2)),
                                                                                  levels(dds$group))) +
                                             xlab(paste0(str_glue("PC{PCx}: "),percentVar[PCx],"% variance")) +
                                             ylab(paste0(str_glue("PC{PCy}: "),percentVar[PCy],"% variance")) + 
                                             theme_bw() + 
                                             ggrepel::geom_text_repel(max.overlaps=5)))
  }
  wrap_plots(out_patchwork)
}
(make_PCA(vsd, ntop=10000, cols="group") | 
    (make_PCA(vsd, ntop=10000, cols="group", PCx = 3, PCy = 4))) +
  plot_layout(guides="collect") + 
  plot_annotation(title = "PCA - All Samples") 

test_clustering <- function(in_dds, ntop) {
  if (ntop > nrow(in_dds)) {
    ntop <- nrow(in_dds)
  }

  mat <- assay(in_dds) 
  col_data <- as.data.frame(colData(in_dds))
    
  # row variances
  vars <- genefilter::rowVars(mat)
  vars_rank <- order(vars, decreasing = TRUE)

  # get most variable genes
  mat <- mat[vars_rank[1:ntop], ]

  mat_PERMANOVA <- mat %>%
    t() %>%
    scale() 
  mat_PERMANOVA_df <- mat_PERMANOVA %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    tibble::rownames_to_column("sample") %>%
    left_join(., as.data.frame(colData(vsd)), by="sample") 

  adonis2(mat_PERMANOVA ~ group, data = mat_PERMANOVA_df, method='eu')
}
res_clustering <- test_clustering(vsd, ntop=10000)
res_clustering

The PERMANOVA test above tests whether the groups are significantly different from each other based on the most variable genes in the dataset. A significant p-value (e.g. < 0.05) indicates that the groups are significantly different from each other, and that the PCA plot is likely to show separation between the groups. Here, we see that the groups appear to be significantly different from each other (p-value = 0.022), indicating that the PCA plot is likely to show separation between the groups.

1.3.2 Volcano plot

Volcano plots are a common way to visualize the results of differential expression analyses. They plot a fold change metric (here, log2FoldChange) on the x-axis and a significance metric on the y-axis (here, the -log10 p-value). Genes that are significantly differentially expressed will appear as points in the upper right or upper left areas of the plot, depending on whether they are upregulated or downregulated, respectively. The directionality of the plot is dependent on which group was specified as the group_test and group_reference in the comparisons.tsv – genes that are higher in your test group (here, “trt”) will show up on the right side of the plot (upregulated). Genes that are higher in your reference group (here, “untrt”) will show up on the left side of the plot (downregulated).

Below is a volcano plot, with labels for the top 10 genes ranked by absolute log fold change.

make_volcano <- function(df, pval_nm, pval_cutoff=0.1){
  # remove genes with NA for pvalue
  df <- df[which(!is.na(df[[pval_nm]])), ]

  # add gene names
  df <- cbind(df, rowData(dds)[rownames(df), 1:4])

  top_genes <- df %>%
    dplyr::arrange(desc(abs(df$log2FoldChange))) %>%
    dplyr::filter(row_number() <= 10) %>%
    rownames()

  df$Sig <- ifelse(df$padj <= pval_cutoff, "Sig", "NS")

  df[[pval_nm]] <- -log10(df[[pval_nm]])

  ggplot(df, aes(x=log2FoldChange, y=.data[[pval_nm]])) +
    geom_point(aes(color=Sig), size=0.6) +
    scale_color_manual(values=c("black", "salmon")) +
    theme_bw() + ylab(str_glue("-log10(", pval_nm,")")) +
    geom_text_repel(data=df[top_genes, ],
                    aes(label=Uniq_syms), max.overlaps=Inf, min.segment.length = 0)
}
make_volcano(as.data.frame(lfc_shrink),
             pval_nm="padj", pval_cutoff=fdr_cutoff)

1.3.4 P value distribution

The distribution of p-values can give us an idea of the number of differentially expressed genes (DE genes) in our analysis, and whether the model used for differential expression is appropriate. We expect the p-values to be uniformly distributed if there are not many DE genes, or anti-conservative (more p-values close to 0) if there are many DE genes. See here for more details about how to interpret these, and again, contact the BBC if you have questions about your results.

ggplot(data = as.data.frame(lfc_shrink) %>%
         dplyr::filter(!is.na(pvalue)),
       aes(x = pvalue)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "gray55",
                 breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.05)) + theme_bw() + theme(plot.title=element_text(size=10))

2 Appendix

Want to make sense of your differential expression results on a broader level?

See gsea_trt_vs_untrt.html for a pathway-level analysis using GSEA (Gene Set Enrichment Analysis), a method for determining whether the changes you see between your groups (trt and untrt) are similar to known pathways/genesets. The report contains a summary of the results, including the top enriched pathways, as well as visualizations of the results. This can help you understand the biological significance of your results and identify potential pathways that are affected by the changes in gene expression.

And, as always, contact the BBC if you have questions about your results!
